<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Association of Colleges – Supplementary written evidence</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Association of Colleges – Supplementary written evidence</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">I noted with interest the oral session on 23 October regarding the clauses in the Draft Deregulation Bill which cover further education and apprenticeships.  In particular, you discussed whether </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">lecturers working in Further Education Colleges need to have qualified teacher status.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The situation in Further Education Colleges is different to that in schools in that the vocational lecturers are often experts in their chosen professional field.  For </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">example, a qualified engineer might teach a class or two a week in the local college very successfully, but might not be a qualified teacher.  The college might encourage such a person to gain qualified teacher status but we do not believe they need the la</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">w to tell them to do so.  Colleges have shown they can manage their own workforces at least as effectively as universities and should, therefore, have the same level of freedom in terms of teacher recruitment.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Colleges will be under the remit of an Ofsted</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> inspection and quality regime which specifically considers whether staff have the right qualifications and experience and I expect the vast majority of their teaching staff will be qualified teachers.  The Minister for Skills and Enterprise</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">, Matthew Hanco</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">ck MP, recently pointed out that 80% of teachers in colleges are qualified with the remaining 19% enrolled on training courses [Commons Hansard, 25 Oct 2013: Column 306W].</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">I am content for you to consider this letter further written evidence from the Asso</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">ciation of Colleges.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Martin Doel OBE</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Chief Executive</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">1</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">1</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> November 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span styl